<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-238-160  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 238 160.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  May 1 1989 v23 n18 p85(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Network Management tools. (Product Spotlight)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hurwicz, Michael.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Network management tools are divided by platforms, usage andvendors, making management of a large network a difficult task.andO;Equipment from one vendor does not work with equipment from othervendors and microcomputer hardware does not work with mainframes.andO;It is usually left to network administrators to tie all thesesystems together and create a single monitoring system for all ofvarious hardware platforms.andP;  Remote management sometimes allowslimited control of hardware connections.andP;  Ultimately, networkmanagers are looking forward to a less complex way of putting allof this together.andP;  Currently, specialized people are needed tosolve troubleshooting problems in a network operation.andP;  Progressis being made toward that end, but no product can yet boast an allencompassing support system that uses a common command structure.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Network ManagementUser NeedsCommunications EquipmentCompatible HardwareResource ManagementProgram Development ToolsModemsLocal Area Networks.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraphtable.andO;Caption:   Resource management (spending and staff). (graph)Search and store (feature measurement). (table)Missing connections. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>